content.content:
/app/answers.json
{
  "recommendation": "AVOID sevoflurane and all other volatile halogenated anesthetic agents. This patient carries a pathogenic RYR1 variant conferring Malignant Hyperthermia Susceptibility (MHS). Sevoflurane is a known MH trigger and is contraindicated. Use non-triggering anesthesia (total intravenous anesthesia, TIVA) instead. Succinylcholine should also be avoided. Ensure dantrolene is immediately available in the operating room. The CACNA1S 'No Result' does not alter management, as MHS status is established by the RYR1 finding.",
  "classification": "Strong",
  "implication": "The patient has a confirmed pathogenic RYR1 variant associated with Malignant Hyperthermia Susceptibility. RYR1 mutations enhance skeletal muscle ryanodine receptor (RyR1) sensitivity, causing uncontrolled sarcoplasmic reticulum Ca2+ release upon exposure to volatile anesthetics such as sevoflurane. This can precipitate a life-threatening MH crisis characterized by hyperthermia, muscle rigidity, rhabdomyolysis, and metabolic acidosis. CACNA1S yielded no result, but this does not affect the clinical conclusion since RYR1-based MHS is already established. MHS is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner; at-risk family members should also be counseled and tested."
}

